#---
# purpose: "runtime Enum list functions preserve protocol-first native list-cons and continuation allocation floors"
# paths: [fz2-run, fz2-interp, fz2-build]
#---
#
# # enum_list_allocations
#
# Pins the protocol-first runtime-library list path for the non-building Enum
# functions:
#
# ```fz
# Enum.count(xs)
# Enum.member?(xs, 3)
# Enum.reduce(xs, 0, fn (x, acc) -> acc + x)
# ```
#
# The program builds one five-element input list, runs those functions through
# the public runtime `Enum` surface, snapshots the specific heap allocation
# counters that express the contract, and prints the list/struct/map heap
# headline.
#
# Target for native JIT/AOT:
#
# - the input list literal allocates five cons cells;
# - `Enum.count/1`, `Enum.member?/2`, and `Enum.reduce/3` allocate no additional
#   cons cells while walking that list;
# - public `Enum.reduce/3` stays a small wrapper over `Enumerable.reduce/3`;
# - static protocol dispatch routes the known list receiver to
#   `Enumerable.List.reduce/3`, which delegates to local `List.reduce_cont/3`;
# - native `Enum.reduce/3` allocates one wrapper closure for the public reducer
#   bridge and uses protocol-control tuple state honestly;
# - no map objects are needed before the stats snapshot;
# - `list_cons_allocs = 5`;
# - `list_cons_bytes = 80`;
# - `closure_allocs = 1`;
# - `closure_bytes = 32`;
# - final list/struct/map heap headline is `368`.
#
# This fixture deliberately excludes `Enum.sort/1`. The current runtime sort is
# a source-level merge sort that builds split/reverse/merge work lists, so it has
# a different allocation contract from the list-consuming functions pinned here.
fn main() do
  xs = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

  dbg(Enum.count(xs))
  dbg(Enum.member?(xs, 3))
  dbg(Enum.reduce(xs, 0, fn (x, acc) -> acc + x end))

  stats = Process.heap_alloc_stats()
  dbg({
    stats[:list_cons_allocs],
    stats[:list_cons_bytes],
    stats[:struct_allocs],
    stats[:struct_bytes],
    stats[:closure_allocs],
    stats[:closure_bytes],
    stats[:scalar_box_allocs],
    stats[:scalar_box_bytes],
    stats[:map_allocs],
    stats[:map_bytes]
  })
  heap_bytes = stats[:list_cons_bytes] + stats[:struct_bytes] + stats[:map_bytes]
  dbg(heap_bytes)
end
